"1131":"1131","1130":"1130","Aft 1131":"after 1131","1170":"1170","Langdon, Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barley, Royston, Hertfordshire, England":"Barley, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","West Langdon, Kent, England":"West Langdon, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Dover, Kent, England":"Dover, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wynanc","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Flemish: variant of   Winant   and   Winand  . In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the Flemish and Dutch cognate <b>Wijnant</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Winant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Anais, Luc.","Walloon and Flemish: variant of   Winand  . In North America, this surname may also be an altered form of the Flemish and Dutch cognate <b>Wijnant</b>. Compare   Wynant  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Wynanc was born in 1104, in Barley, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Hugh d'Auberville in 1124, in Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died after 1131."},"et":{"1104–Aft 1131":"1104–pärast 1131","1100–1131":"1100–1131","1128–1189":"1128–1189","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1104–1131":"1104–1131","Bef 1131":"enne 1131","Bef 1130":"enne 1130","1128":"1128","1104":"1104","1124":"1124","1189":"1189","about 1128":"umbes 1128","1100":"1100","1131":"1131","1130":"1130","Aft 1131":"pärast 1131","1170":"1170","Langdon, Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barley, Royston, Hertfordshire, England":"Barley, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","West Langdon, Kent, England":"West Langdon, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dover, Kent, England":"Dover, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1104–Aft 1131":"1104–1131 jälkeen","1100–1131":"1100–1131","1128–1189":"1128–1189","1130–1170":"1130–1170","1104–1131":"1104–1131","Bef 1131":"ennen vuotta 1131","Bef 1130":"ennen vuotta 1130","1128":"1128","1104":"1104","1124":"1124","1189":"1189","about 1128":"noin 1128","1100":"1100","1131":"1131","1130":"1130","Aft 1131":"1131 jälkeen","1170":"1170","Langdon, Kent, England":"Kent, England","Barley, Royston, Hertfordshire, England":"Barley, Hertfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","West Langdon, Kent, England":"